# 25.Real project use:
You can explain it like this:

In one of my GCP migration projects, sensitive data needed to be encrypted before loading into downstream systems. We used a pre-built Dataflow template for encryption. Cloud Composer (Airflow) orchestrated the workflow and passed runtime parameters such as input file location, output location, encryption configuration, and project details to the Dataflow template. Dataflow processed the data in a distributed manner, encrypted the required fields, and wrote the encrypted output for further processing.
This is one of the most common senior Data Engineer Dataflow questions.

NiFi / GCS
     ↓
BigQuery Stage
     ↓
Composer DAG
     ↓
Dataflow Encryption Template
     ↓
BigQuery Secure Layer
     ↓
SCD1 / SCD2 Transformations
     ↓
Business Tables
     ↓
Tableau / Reporting

Q: What parameters were passed to the template?
Answer:
Input file path
Output file path
Project ID
Service account
KMS key/encryption configuration
Environment-specific settings (dev, pre-prod, prod)


> Sample Dataflow Template :Sample Airflow DAG Triggering Dataflow Template

from airflow import DAG
from airflow.providers.google.cloud.operators.dataflow import DataflowStartFlexTemplateOperator

encrypt_job = DataflowStartFlexTemplateOperator(
    task_id="encrypt_file",
    project_id="my-project",
    location="us-central1",

    body={
        "launchParameter": {
            "jobName": "encrypt-job",

            "containerSpecGcsPath":
            "gs://templates/encryption-template.json",

            "parameters": {
                "inputFile":
                "gs://raw-bucket/customer.csv",

                "outputFile":
                "gs://encrypted-bucket/customer.csv",

                "kmsKey":
                "projects/client-project/locations/us/keyRings/prod/cryptoKeys/pii-key"
            }
        }
    }
)



Achieve Reusability : Store parameter json or key-value pair file in gcs bucket
To make the solution reusable across datasets, I created a parameterized Dataflow template instead of hardcoding dataset or table names. The template accepted runtime parameters such as source dataset, source table, target dataset, target table, columns to encrypt, and the KMS key reference. Cloud Composer read these values from a configuration file/table and passed them to the Dataflow job at runtime. This allowed us to use the same template for multiple datasets and environments (dev, pre-prod, prod) without modifying the code, reducing maintenance effort and ensuring consistent encryption logic across all pipelines.


